body:
### Problem

The new neovim commenting feature is great. However, with the new commenting feature, the program breaks on commenting lines containing comments for c/cpp programs. For example consider

```
int a = 1;
/*int b = 2;*/
int c = 3;
````

Commenting these together by selecting using 'V' would lead to

```
/*int a = 1;*/
/*/*int b = 2;*/*/
/*int c = 3;*/
````

which is not valid C/C++ code. A simple fix for this would be to change the commentstring to '// %s' (in runtime/ftplugin/c.lua). Ideally, from reading previous issues, it seems this should be raised on vim/vim, but this is not a issue for vim due to the lack of inbuilt individual line based commenting (last I checked, feel free to correct me here). I add the same in my ftplugins, but a good default would be better.

### Expected behavior

Commenting

```
int a = 1;
// int b = 2;
int c = 3;
````

would lead to 
```
// int a = 1;
// // int b = 2;
// int c = 3;
````

(and appropriately for /*%s*/)

Edit: I can submit a PR if required, just wanted to confirm if this would be an acceptable change.

comment_data.body:
Normally you are right, we would ask you to submit this change to Vim (and you still could, if you want). But I strongly suspect that this change (and request) would not be welcome there, and we have our own `ftplugin` already anyway. So in this instance I am actually inclined to make an exception -- not least of all because Neovim itself uses that form for comments in its codebase.

Only problem is that we would now need to go through the "default" commentstrings and decide whether they should remain the current default or be changed to match C.

@neovim/core what do you think?
